Free-trade fanatics.
From Cambridge — — I was recently invited to guest lecture in a globalization course taught by two Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you."
One of them had warned me beforehand: "These students are all ardent supporters of globalization."
He once had the students in his first class choose between free trade and import restrictions, and more than 90% opted for the former.
And this was before they even started on the magic of comparative advantage.
We know that posing the same questions to representative samples – not Harvard students – in a genuine survey would yield a sharply different result.
In the United States, the ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions is 2:1.
But the answers from Harvard students would not come as a great surprise.
Because individuals with higher technology and better education tend to be more inclined to support free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students have already anticipated their future prospects and made their decision accordingly.
Or they simply do not understand how trade works.
Ultimately, when I met with them, I specifically asked the same question in a different form, and emphasized the possible distribution effects of trade.
The consensus on fair trade has vanished completely, even more quickly than I had anticipated.
At the outset, I asked if they agreed to my conducting an especially magical experiment.
I chose Nicholas and John as volunteers, then told them I had a way to make the $200 in Nicholas's account vanish – poof! – while simultaneously adding $300 to John's account, and that the social engineering feat could add an additional $100 of value to the class as a whole.
So, would they let me pull off this little trick?
Only a small fraction of the class was resolute in their agreement, many were indecisive, and even more were opposed to implementing this shift.
The students who were pro-free trade were largely from the business and economics majors.
It's clear that the students can hardly stomach this massive income redistribution, even when the entire economic pie has been expanded.
I then asked, why most of them instinctively endorsed free trade, while free trade would actually lead to a similar, if not a more substantial, redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
They looked taken aback.
Let's assume Nicholas and John each run a small company that competes with each other.
John worked harder, saved more, invested more, and produced better products, so he not only had an additional $300 but also pushed Nicholas's company out of the market and resulted in a $200 loss for him.
How many students were in favor of this change?
This time, almost all of them voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed.
I then presented another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
If John had pushed Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or would they be outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are still being developed?
Or would they be employing child labor in Indonesia?
This level of support for change decreases in turn with the options mentioned above.
Technological innovation, like trade, can also lead to certain groups being in a more disadvantaged position; what are your views on this?
Only a few students were willing to curb technological progress.
To most people, the idea of banning light bulb production to save candle makers' jobs is utterly absurd.
Therefore, students' opposition is not necessarily to redistribution, but rather to certain specific forms of it.
Like most people, they are concerned with the fairness of the process.
If we are to make a judgment about the results of redistribution, we must first know the objective environment that gives rise to these results.
We won't be resentful of Bill Gates or Warren Buffett's enormous wealth, even if some of their rivals have been struggling, because they and their competitors are all operating under the same basic rules, facing similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become wealthy through deceit, labor law violations, environmental destruction, or by relying on foreign government subsidies, our attitudes would be vastly different.
If we can't tolerate redistribution achieved through violating the moral principles widely accepted domestically, why should we be comfortable with it simply because it involves international trade?
When we expect the redistributive effects to be achieved equally in the long run, with everyone ultimately benefiting as a result, we are likely to be indifferent to the transfer of income.
This is why we believe that even though technology may bring short-term negative consequences for some people, we still want to promote its development.
Meanwhile, when trade repeatedly hits the same group of people - low-skilled blue-collar workers with limited education - we begin to worry about globalization.
But many economists have turned a deaf ear to these obvious distinctions.
They tend to attribute their concerns about globalization to foolishly selfish trade protectionism or ignorance, without realizing that the most crucial issue at stake is actually a moral one.
Due to their inability to grasp that international trade sometimes – though certainly not always – can lead to redistributive consequences that we would find unacceptable at home, these economists have been unable to intervene in public discussions in a meaningful way.
If they can't stand on moral ground, how can they confidently defend trade?
When globalization occasionally raises a tricky issue related to the legitimation of redistributive consequences, we shouldn't reflexively resort to restricting trade as a response.
There are many difficult trade-offs to consider in this regard, including the possibility that globalization may lead to more severe wealth deprivation for people in other parts of the world than for victims in the United States.
But democratic countries should have a more informed discussion about this and make more deliberate and thoughtful decisions as a result.
While an approach that merely romanticizes globalization because it has enlarged the pie will inevitably erode the legitimacy of globalization itself in the long run.
